I tried this code:
[playgroud](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=33a114f65e2288f9529bd2624b0c5568)
```rust
use std::future::Future;

pub struct Producer {
    params: Vec<String>,
}

fn spawn<T>(_: T) where
    T: Future + Send + 'static,
    T::Output: Send + 'static,
{}

impl Producer {
    async fn update(&self) {
        let _fetched = self
            .fetch(self.params.iter().map(|s| -> &str { s }))
            .await;
    }
    
    pub async fn fetch(&self, params: impl IntoIterator<Item = &str>) {
        self.inner_fetch(params.into_iter()).await
    }

    pub async fn inner_fetch(&self, params: impl Iterator<Item = &str>) {
        todo!()
    }
}

fn main() {
    let producer = Producer {
        params: Vec::new(),
    };

    spawn(async move { producer.update().await });
}

```

I expected to see this happen: code compiling, or some error showing how could I fix this

Instead, this happened: 

```
error: implementation of `std::iter::Iterator` is not general enough
    --> src/main.rs:33:5
     |
33   |       spawn(async move { producer.update().await });
     |       ^^^^^ implementation of `std::iter::Iterator` is not general enough
     |
     = note: `std::iter::Iterator` would have to be implemented for the type `std::slice::Iter<'0, std::string::String>`, for any lifetime `'0`...
     = note: ...but `std::iter::Iterator` is actually implemented for the type `std::slice::Iter<'1, std::string::String>`, for some specific lifetime `'1`

```

